  "text": "Kubernetes RBAC ClusterRole privilege escalation validation is enforced through a multi-layered mechanism that prevents users from granting permissions they don't hold. The core implementation is distributed across several key files:\n\n## Escalation Check Functions\nThe primary escalation checking logic is in pkg/registry/rbac/escalation_check.go. This file contains three critical functions:\n\n1. **EscalationAllowed**: Checks if the user belongs to the 'system:masters' group, which is a superuser group that allows privileged loopback connections and can always perform escalation.\n\n2. **RoleEscalationAuthorized**: Explicitly checks if a user has been authorized to perform the 'escalate' verb on Role or ClusterRole resources. This function constructs an AttributesRecord with the 'escalate' verb and queries the authorizer to determine if the decision is Allow.\n\n3. **BindingAuthorized**: Checks if a user has the 'bind' verb permission on the specific role being referenced in a RoleBinding or ClusterRoleBinding.\n\n## Policy-Based Storage Enforcement\nEscalation validation is enforced at the storage layer in four policybased storage implementations:\n\n1. **pkg/registry/rbac/clusterrole/policybased/storage.go**: Prevents creation/update of ClusterRoles with escalating permissions. For ClusterRoles with aggregationRules, it requires cluster-admin privileges (full authority on *).\n\n2. **pkg/registry/rbac/clusterrolebinding/policybased/storage.go**: Validates ClusterRoleBinding creation/update by checking if the user either has escalation allowed, explicit bind authorization, or owns the permissions in the referenced ClusterRole.\n\n3. **pkg/registry/rbac/role/policybased/storage.go**: Validates Role creation/update with the same escalation checks as ClusterRoles (namespaced variant).\n\n4. **pkg/registry/rbac/rolebinding/policybased/storage.go**: Validates RoleBinding creation/update (namespaced variant).\n\n## Permission Coverage Validation\nThe core escalation prevention logic is in pkg/registry/rbac/validation/rule.go through the **ConfirmNoEscalation** function. This function:\n\n1. Extracts the user from context\n2. Calls the RuleResolver to get all rules the user currently has\n3. Uses the Covers function from staging/src/k8s.io/component-helpers/auth/rbac/validation/policy_comparator.go to check if the user's current rules cover (encompass) the rules they're trying to grant\n4. Returns an error if the user is attempting to grant permissions not currently held\n\nThe **Covers** function performs the actual permission comparison by:\n1. Breaking down servant rules into atomic rule tuples (one verb, resource, and resource name per rule)\n2. Checking if each atomic rule is covered by at least one owner rule\n3. Verifying that wildcards and exact matches are properly evaluated for verbs, API groups, resources, and resource names\n\n## Version Adaptation\nThe pkg/registry/rbac/validation/internal_version_adapter.go file provides **ConfirmNoEscalationInternal** which converts internal version PolicyRules to v1 PolicyRules before calling ConfirmNoEscalation, enabling consistent validation across API versions.\n\n## Rule Compaction\nThe pkg/registry/rbac/validation/policy_compact.go file provides **CompactRules** which optimizes error messages by consolidating simple rules that only differ by verbs, reducing the verbosity of escalation denial error messages.\n\n## Bootstrap Policies\nThe plugin/pkg/auth/authorizer/rbac/bootstrappolicy/controller_policy.go file defines default bootstrap ClusterRoles that include the 'escalate' verb for specific system controllers (like the clusterrole-aggregation-controller) that need permission to mutate ClusterRoles in specific ways.\n\n## Attack Prevention\nThis implementation prevents privilege escalation by:\n1. Restricting the 'escalate' verb to authorized users only\n2. Blocking creation/update of roles that would grant permissions the user doesn't currently have\n3. Requiring explicit 'bind' authorization or permission coverage for role bindings\n4. Enforcing these rules consistently across both cluster-scoped (ClusterRole/ClusterRoleBinding) and namespace-scoped (Role/RoleBinding) resources"
}

